# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: general-manager-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:general-manager-baseball/1902-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1902 throughout the world.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1902-in-baseball] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] The **1905 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1905 season.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] The National League (NL) champion New York Giants defeated the American League (AL) champion Philadelphia Athletics, with the Giants winning 4 games to 1, now in a best-4-of-7 format.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] Four of the five games featured duels between future Hall of Fame pitchers.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] The games were the second edition of the World Series after the initial meeting in 1903, since the 1904 season ended with no Series held, and the first to be officially sanctioned by the leagues and the National Baseball Commission.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] This was the first professional sports championship ever won by a New York City-based team.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] Games 1 and 3 were played in Philadelphia; games 2, 4, 5 in New York.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] Three of those, over a six-day span, were pitched and won by Christy Mathewson.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] Before the Series began, the Athletics were already at a major disadvantage.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] For the Series, they were without the services of Rube Waddell, who was arguably their best pitcher that year.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] The reason for Waddell's absence was listed as a shoulder injury from some sort of 'wrestling match' with teammate Andy Coakley, though in years since some have speculated that Waddell was actually bribed or 'paid off' to fake the injury and thus not play in the Series.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] Philadelphia manager Connie Mack, however, refused to believe this theory, finding it ridiculous.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] John McGraw, the Giants' manager, had previously referred to the Athletics as a "white elephant", which the club defiantly adopted as a symbolic mascot.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] At the conference at home plate before Game 1, A's team captain Lave Cross gave McGraw a wrapped package, which turned out to contain a toy white elephant.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] McGraw responded with a big grin, and the crowd laughed.[Philadelphia *Inquirer*, October 10, 2005, p.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] 10] McGraw and the Giants would have the last laugh, easily defeating the A's in the Series.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] The opening game was a pitchers' duel between Christy Mathewson and Eddie Plank.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] Both got out of jams, shutting the opposing offense down.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] In the Giants' top of the fifth, Mathewson singled, but was forced by Roger Bresnahan, who stole second shortly afterwards.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] After George Browne popped out, Mike Donlin singled to left, scoring Bresnahan and advancing Donlin to second.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] After Dan McGann walked, Sam Mertes doubled, bringing home Donlin.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] In the Athletics' half of the sixth, Ossee Schreckengost doubled and advanced to third on a wild pitch, but did not score, and was the lone runner to reach third base against Mathewson in the entire series.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] The Giants added an insurance run in the ninth, when Billy Gilbert scored on Bresnahan's single.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] This was the first of Mathewson's three complete-game shutouts, a World Series record that may never be matched.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] The A's called on Chief Bender to turn the tables on the Giants.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] His opponent was 21-game winner "Iron Man" Joe McGinnity.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] The game was scoreless until the top of the third.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] Ossee Schreckengost, leading off, reached on a Dan McGann's error.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] Bender sacrificed, moving Schreckengost to second.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] After a groundout by Topsy Hartsel moved Schreckengost to third, Bris Lord singled to left and drove Ossee home with an unearned run.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] The slim margin held until the top of the eighth, when the A's scored multiple times.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] With one out, Schreckengost was once again the catalyst, singling to center.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] After Bender flied out to right field, Hartsel's double scored Schreckengost all the way from first (helped by an error from Bresnahan), and a single by Lord brought Hartsel home, making it 3–0 in favor of the A's with all three runs unearned.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] Bender continued to cruise, got out of late-inning jams and ended up with a complete-game shutout that tied the series at one game each.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] Christy Mathewson once again took the mound for the Giants in Game 3.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] Opposing him this time was Andy Coakley, who hit the first batter he faced, Roger Bresnahan, with a pitch.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] A single to right by Mike Donlin moved Bresnahan to third with one out.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] Dan McGann singled to right, bringing Bresnahan home.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] An error by Danny Murphy scored Donlin and put Sam Mertes on base.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] Bill Dahlen walked, loading the bases with one out, but Art Devlin hit into a double play to end the rally.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] The Giants put the game away in the top of the fifth.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] George Browne singled and went to second on the throw to third base.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] Donlin was walked intentionally, setting up a possible inning-ending double play, but things continued to crumble for Coakley and the A's.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] McGann reached on another error by Danny Murphy, reloading the bases and scoring a run.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] Mertes singled, reloading the bases and driving in another run.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] Bill Dahlen hit into a force play at second, scoring Donlin.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] After Dahlen stole second, Devlin singled, bringing home McGann and sending Dahlen to third.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] Devlin then stole second and Dahlen stole home on a double steal, scoring the fifth and last run of the Giants' fifth.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] They scored two more runs in the top of the ninth, when McGann doubled home Browne and Donlin.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] Mathewson pitched his second complete-game shutout, giving the Giants a 2–1 lead in the series.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] This was the first 9–0 World Series game—the next one occurred when the Cubs shut out the Tigers by that lopsided score in Game 1 in 1945, although Detroit ended up taking that series four games to three.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] Eddie Plank returned for the A's against Joe McGinnity for the Giants in Game 4.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] Both left men on base in scoring position early on, and kept the game scoreless until the bottom of the fourth, when Sam Mertes led off the inning by reaching on an error by Monte Cross.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] After Bill Dahlen flied to right Art Devlin grounded out, moving Mertes to second.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] With two outs, Billy Gilbert singled to left, bringing Mertes home for the only run of the game, McGinnity outdueling Plank 1–0 and giving the Giants a three-games-to-one lead.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] The Giants looked to wrap up the series behind the perennial Christy Mathewson, who faced Chief Bender this time.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] In the eighth, the Giants got an insurance run when Mathewson scored on George Browne's ground out after Roger Bresnahan's double had sent him to third with less than two out.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1905-world-series] Mathewson then took the mound for the top of the ninth and induced three ground outs, thereby completing arguably the single greatest performance by any player in World Series history with his third complete-game shutout of the series.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] The **1909 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1909 season.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] The sixth edition of the World Series, it featured the National League (NL) champion Pittsburgh Pirates against the American League (AL) champion Detroit Tigers.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] The Pirates won the Series in seven games to capture their first championship of the modern Major League Baseball era and the second championship in the club's history.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] This was the first major professional sports championship ever won by a Pittsburgh-based team.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] This Series is best remembered for featuring two of the very best players of the time, Pittsburgh shortstop Honus Wagner, and Detroit outfielder Ty Cobb.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] Sites: games 1, 2 in Pittsburgh; games 3, 4 in Detroit; game 5 in Pittsburgh; games 6, 7 in Detroit.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] The Pirates had won the National League pennant in 1909 behind the brilliant play of Honus Wagner, who led the league with a .339 batting average and 100 runs batted in.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] Detroit returned for their third consecutive Fall Classic, determined to erase the memories of their previous efforts.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] The Tigers were also backed up by the heavy bat of Ty Cobb (who had just won his third consecutive American League batting title) and a formidable pitching staff.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] They might have finally won the Series in their third try, had it not been for Pirates rookie Babe Adams.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] Manager Fred Clarke started him, on a hunch, in Game 1.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] Adams won that game and two more, setting a World Series record for rookies.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] The Tigers thus became the first AL team to win three consecutive pennants and the first team to lose three straight World Series (the New York Giants would lose three straight Series from 1911 to 1913).
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] The Pirates ran at will against the weak Detroit catching corps, stealing 18 bases in seven games.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] For the first time, four umpires were used at the same time, with the standard plate umpire and base umpire along with two outfield umpires.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] On June 14, 2009, the series' 100th anniversary was celebrated, when the Tigers and Pirates played each other in Pittsburgh.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] Both teams wore throwback uniforms similar to those worn in 1909.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] The stadium's public address and sound systems were also turned off, simulating the game conditions in 1909.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] Ty Cobb had a fairly quiet Series, going 6-for-26 with two stolen bases and one caught stealing.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] There is a long-standing legend that Cobb, standing on first base, called the German-ancestored Honus Wagner a "krauthead", told him he was going to steal second, and was not only thrown out but that Wagner tagged him in the mouth, ball in hand, drawing blood from Cobb's lip.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] However, an examination of the play-by-play does not indicate that such a play occurred.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] In the one "caught stealing" charged to Cobb, during the first inning of Game 4, he was actually safe at second due to a throwing error by first baseman Bill Abstein.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] This story is largely attributed to the creative press at the time, and Wagner and Cobb were actually on good terms.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] Rookie Babe Adams, who had compiled a 12–3 record during the regular season, unexpectedly drew the start for Game 1.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] He responded with a six-hit, 4–1 victory sparked by Clarke's game-tying home run in the bottom of the fourth inning.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] The Tigers began their 7–2 comeback win (after a two-run Pirate bottom of the first) with three runs in the top of the third, tying the Series at one game apiece.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] Honus Wagner had three hits, three RBI and three stolen bases as the Pirates regained the lead in the Series, two games to one.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] The win-swapping continued with Detroit taking Game 4.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] Tiger ace George Mullin threw a five-hit shutout while striking out 10 Pirates, again evening the Series at two games apiece.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] Babe Adams threw another six-hitter, for an 8–4 triumph and a 3–2 Series lead for his Pirates.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] Mullin, after being roughed up for three first-inning runs, surrendered only one more and wound up with the win, knotting the Series at three games apiece.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] With the Series coming down to a climactic seventh game (the first to go the distance), Pittsburgh's Fred Clarke went with two-game winner Babe Adams as his pitcher, while Detroit Manager Hugh Jennings decided on Bill Donovan, a complete-game winner in Game 2.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] He hit the first Pirate batter and went on to walk six in the first two innings.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] He was pulled after three with Adams confidently holding a 2–0 lead.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] Pittsburgh never looked back, as Babe nailed his third six-hitter and third win of the Series for an 8–0 championship victory.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] Honus Wagner continued to prove his Cooperstown worthiness by hitting .333, with seven RBI and six stolen bases (the latter total standing as a Series record until Lou Brock surpassed it in 1967).
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] On the other side, Ty Cobb did not fare as well.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] Appearing in what would be his last Series (although he would remain active through 1928), Cobb batted only .231 although he did lead the Tigers, losers of their third Series in three years, with six RBI.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] It was the first time that one team won the odd-numbered games; the other, the even; it did not happen again until 1962.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] The championship was recorded by Essanay Co., and sold double the expected number of copies.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] Kennedy speculated that the film would set a world record for sales.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] No two professional sports teams from Detroit and Pittsburgh would play for a major professional sports championship again until the 2008 Stanley Cup Final between the Detroit Red Wings and Pittsburgh Penguins.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] The Pirates would return to the World Series in 1925, where they overcame a 3–1 series deficit and defeated the Washington Senators in seven games.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] This was the third straight Would Series loss for the Tigers.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1909-world-series] The Tigers would not play in another Fall Classic for 25 years, where they lost yet again in seven games, this time to the St.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] The **1921 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1921 season.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] The 18th edition of the World Series, it matched the National League (NL) champion New York Giants and the American League (AL) champion New York Yankees.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] The Series matched two distinct teams in strategy with the Giants, dedicated practitioners of the dead-ball era's "inside game" and the Yankees, who relied on the "power game" exemplified by Babe Ruth, who was coming off of what was arguably his best year ever statistically.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] This was the first World Series appearance by the Yankees, who have gone on to play in the Series a record 41 times.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] The 1921 Series was a closely contested matchup that ended on a double play featuring a baserunning miscue.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] It was also the last of four World Series to use the best-of-nine format, which had been used in the 1903, 1919, and the 1920 editions.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] The following year, the World Series permanently switched to a best-of-seven game format where it has remained ever since.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] It was also the first World Series to be broadcast over radio.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] The Series was the last of the experimental best-five-of-nine series, which the Giants won five games to three.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] This marked the first time in World Series history that the series occurred at a single site.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] It happened again the following year in the same place with the same two teams, in 1944 at St.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] Louis' Sportsman's Park between the Cardinals and the Browns, and then again in 2020 when the COVID-19 pandemic necessitated the first-ever neutral-site Series played at Globe Life Field in Arlington, Texas between the Los Angeles Dodgers and Tampa Bay Rays.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] For New Yorkers, this was the first subway Series in World Series history.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] It was also the first World Series to be broadcast on radio, with Grantland Rice covering the games live through Pittsburgh's KDKA.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] It was rebroadcast on WBZ in Massachusetts.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] Announcer Tommy Cowan also recreated the games over Westinghouse-owned WJZ in Newark as he listened to phoned-in reports from the stadium.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] Because of an infected arm and a bad knee (which he wrenched in Game 5), Babe Ruth did not start the final three games, appearing only as a pinch-hitter in the final inning of Game 8.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] Following the Series, Ruth and Bob Meusel did some postseason barnstorming, against the rules for Series participants at that time.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] Both were suspended for a number of games at the start of the 1922 season.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] Ruth filed a personal appeal with Commissioner Landis, who upheld their suspensions but agreed to rescind the rule effective the end of that season.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] Miller, described as "a big baseball fan" by *The New York Times*, made plans to attend games as a guest of the Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] The Series drew fans to New York City from across the continent, from as far west as California and Mexico to as far south as Cuba.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] Hotels were booked up, and both the New York Central and Pennsylvania Railroads made plans to add cars and run their trains in sections if necessary to handle the extra traffic expected.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] Davis, then the Governor of Ohio, was expected to attend the games as were several other VIPs of the time.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] The two were teammates on the old Baltimore Orioles in earlier seasons.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] Several players on both teams didn't start the 1921 season with either the Giants or the Yankees, and several others moved to other teams during the regular season earlier that year.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] For the Giants, Johnny Rawlings, Irish Meusel, Casey Stengel and Red Causey started the season as Philadelphia Phillies, who finished last in the National League that year.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] Outfielder Bill Cunningham had played for the Seattle Rainiers of the Pacific Coast League, nor did Cozy Dolan or Red Shea start the season with the Giants, while the Yankees acquired outfielder Elmer Miller and pitcher Tom Rogers during the season.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] Nonparticipants from either team in the Series included Curt Walker, Lee King, Johnny Monroe, Rube Benton, Goldie Rapp, Ping Bodie, Tom Sheehan and Tom Connelly.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] This was the first of three consecutive matchups between the Yankees and Giants (1921–1923) and marked the only time (as of 2023) that three straight World Series featured the same two clubs.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] Brothers Bob and Irish Meusel played against each other in each of those three series, making them the first set of brothers to play against each other on opposing teams in a World Series or any Big Four championship series.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] Mays pitched a complete game 5-hit shutout, Frankie Frisch getting 4 of those hits off of Mays in a losing cause for the Giants.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] This was the first World Series game victory for the Yankees.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] Pitching Ruth carefully, the Giants walked the Babe three times; but after the third walk he stole second and then third base, much to the delight of Yankee fans.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] But when he slid into third, he scraped his elbow severely and the site became infected.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] Hoyt held the Giants to two hits, the Yankees jumping to a 2–0 lead in the series.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] After getting outscored 6–0 in the first two games of this series and falling behind 4–0 in the top of the third, the Giants tied it with four runs of their own in the bottom half.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] Later on, an 8-run 7th inning highlighted by Ross Youngs' bases loaded triple turned the tide as the Giants got their first win of this series.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] Ruth was taken out in the eighth after again scraping his elbow sliding into a base.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] The Yankees announced after the game that the elbow would have to be lanced and that he would not return for the rest of the Series.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] Ruth suited up, but stayed on the bench during batting practice.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] When the game began, however, to everyone's surprise, he popped out of the dugout and jogged to his outfield position.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] He kept touching his bandaged arm throughout the game.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] Despite the injury, he got two hits including a ninth-inning homer, his first World Series home run as well as the first World Series home run in Yankees franchise history.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] But the Giants won the game and tied the series at 2–2.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] Ruth's arm was still bandaged, but he played again.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] In the fourth, with the score tied 1–1, he shocked everyone by bunting and beating it out.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] His teammate Meusel then doubled, scoring Ruth all the way from first base for the go-ahead run in a 3–1 Yankee win.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] The Giants battled back from 3–0 and 5–3 deficits to take Game 6.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] Phil Douglas scattered eight hits and held the Yankees to one run, the Giants winning 2–1 on Frank Snyder's RBI double in the seventh inning.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] Facing elimination, Yankee manager Miller Huggins sent Ruth out to pinch-hit in the bottom of the ninth.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] The Babe, nursing both elbow and knee injuries, had sat out this game and missed all of Games 6 and 7.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] The bases were empty and the Yankees still trailed by the lone run of the game scored by the Giants in the top of the first.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] A HR would tie the game, and a hit or a walk would give the Yankees a chance.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1921-world-series] But Ruth grounded out, and shortly afterwards Frank Baker hit into a double play after a walk by Aaron Ward who was thrown out at third base for the final out of the Series, giving the Giants their first world championship since Christy Mathewson's record three complete shutouts in 1905.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] The **1922 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1922 season.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] The 19th edition of the World Series, it matched the National League (NL) champion New York Giants against the American League (AL) champion New York Yankees.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] The Giants beat the Yankees in five games (four games to zero, with one tie) in the first Series with a permanent best-of-seven format.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] By now, the term "World Series" was being used frequently, as opposed to "World's Series".
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] The Giants held Babe Ruth in check (he batted only .118 with just one RBI) and scored just enough runs to win each of the games outside the controversial Game 2 tie.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] That game was called on account of darkness, but many thought there was sufficient light to have played some more innings (the sun was still in the sky), and there were some suspicions that one or both teams might have "allowed" the tie to happen to increase the overall gate receipts.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] Commissioner Landis was among those who was dissatisfied with the result.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] One story is that Landis asked Umpire Hildebrand, "Why the Sam Hill did you call the game?" The umpire answered, "There was a temporary haze on the field." The game decision was in the hands of the umpires, but the Commissioner's Office controlled the gate receipts.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] Landis ordered the money, more than $120,000, turned over to World War I charities, thus nullifying any impropriety.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] The tied game would turn out to be the third (and final) tied game in the history of the World Series.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] The other two tied games occurred in 1907 and 1912.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] No ties are possible under later rules, which allow for suspension of a tied game and resumption of it at a later date, as with Game 5 of the 2008 World Series.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] As of 2024, this is the last time the Giants have won the World Series at home, as their next five championships were all clinched on the road.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] This would prove to be Giants' manager John McGraw's third and final World Series win.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] The game and Series remained scoreless until the sixth inning.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] Whitey Witt tripled off of Art Nehf, then was cut down at home trying to score on a fielder's choice, but a Babe Ruth hit got the run home.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] The Yankees added another run next inning on Aaron Ward's sacrifice fly with runners on second and third.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] A three-run Giant rally in the eighth knocked out Yankee starter Bullet Joe Bush, who allowed four straight leadoff singles, the last of which to Irish Meusel scoring two. and the winning run coming off reliever Waite Hoyt on a Ross Youngs sacrifice fly.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] This was the controversial tie (see above).
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] Pitchers Bob Shawkey and Jesse Barnes went all 10 innings.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] The Giants scored all three runs in the first on Irish Meusel's three-run home run after two singles.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] The Yankees scored a run in the first on Wally Pipp's RBI single after Joe Dugan reached second on an error and another run in the fourth on Aaron Ward's home run.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] The Yankees had tied the game in the eighth on doubles by Babe Ruth and Bob Meusel, but that is the way the game ended.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] Knuckleballer Jack Scott kept the Yankees off the board.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] In the bottom of the third with runners on second and third, Frankie Frisch's sacrifice fly and Irish Meusel's RBI single scored a run each for the Giants, who added an insurance run in the seventh on Frankie Frisch's RBI single.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] This contest moved along even faster than Game 3.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] It was over in a snappy 1:41, with Giants pitcher Hugh McQuillan going the distance for a 4-3 win.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] The Yankees scored two runs in the first on back-to-back singles by Wally Pipp and Bob Meusel, but in the fifth after a leadoff single and double, Dave Bancroft's two-run single tied the game.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] After a single and groundout, Irish Meusel's groundout and Ross Youngs's RBI single scored a run each.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] Aaron Ward's home run in the seventh cut the Giants' lead to one, but the Yankees did not score after that.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] Art Nehf's five-hit pitching combined with a three-run eighth inning won the Series for the Giants.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] The Yankees scored a run in the first when Joe Dugan singled with one out, moved to second on a sacrifice bunt and scored on Wally Pipp's RBI single, but in the bottom of the second with runners on second and third, Bill Cunningham's two-run single gave the Giants the lead.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] The Yankees tied the game in the fifth on Bullet Joe Bush's RBI single after a walk and single, then took the lead on Everett Scott's sacrifice fly with runners on second and third.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] The decisive rally began with a Heinie Groh single and Frankie Frisch double.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] After an intentional walk to Ross Youngs, a two-run single by High Pockets Kelly put the Giants on top.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] The next batter, Lee King, inserted in the outfield that inning for defensive purposes, delivered an RBI single to make it 5-3, and that's how it ended.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] This was the second of three consecutive matchups between the Yankees and Giants (1921–1923) marked the only time (as of 2023), that three straight World Series featured the same two clubs.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] The Giants became the second NL team to win back-to-back World Series, following the Chicago Cubs in 1907–08, and remained the last until the 1975–76 Cincinnati Reds.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1922-world-series] This also remains the last World Series to be won by the Giants at home, as their championships of 1933 and 1954 (for New York) and 2010, 2012 and 2014 (for San Francisco) were all clinched as the visiting team.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] The **1925 World Series** was the championship series of the 1925 Major League Baseball season.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] The 22nd edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff, played between the National League (NL) champion Pittsburgh Pirates and the American League (AL) champion Washington Senators, the defending World Series champion.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] The Pirates defeated the defending champion Senators in seven games to win the series, becoming the first team in North American sports history to overcome a 3–1 series deficit to win a playoff series.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] In a reversal of fortune on all counts from the previous 1924 World Series, when Washington's Walter Johnson had come back from two losses to win the seventh and deciding game, Johnson dominated in Games 1 and 4, but lost Game 7.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] The Senators built up a 3–1 Series lead.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] After Pittsburgh won the next two games, Johnson again took the mound for Game 7, and carried a 6–4 lead into the bottom of the seventh inning.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] But errors by shortstop Roger Peckinpaugh in both the seventh and eighth innings led to four unearned runs, and the Pirates become the first team in a best-of-seven Series to overcome a 3–1 Series deficit to win the championship.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] Peckinpaugh, the Senators' regular shortstop and the 1925 American League Most Valuable Player, had a tough Series in the field, committing a record eight errors.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] In the next day's *The New York Times*, James Harrison wrote "In a grave of mud was buried Walter Johnson's ambition to join the select panel of pitchers who have won three victories in one World Series.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] Twice in Game 7 the visiting Senators held leads of at least three runs over the Pirates but failed to hold them.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] In fact, after the top of the first inning, Washington led 4–0.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] Nevertheless, Pittsburgh eventually won the game, scoring three runs in the bottom of the eighth inning to turn a 6–7 deficit into a 9–7 lead.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] To date, the four-run deficit is the largest ever overcome in the seventh game of the World Series.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] It was the largest comeback in a World Series clinching game until 2024.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] A memorable play occurred during the eighth inning of Game 3.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] The Senators' Sam Rice ran after an Earl Smith line drive hit into right center field.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] Rice made a diving "catch" into the temporary stands, but did not emerge with the ball for approximately 15 seconds.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] The Pirates contested the play, saying a fan probably stuffed the ball into Rice's glove.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] The call stood and Rice parried questions about the incident for the rest of his life—never explicitly saying whether he had or had not really made the catch.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] His typical answer (including to Commissioner Landis, who said it was a good answer) was always "The umpire said I caught it." Rice left a sealed letter at the Hall of Fame to be opened after his death.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] This was Walter Johnson's second and final World Series appearance.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] By the time the original Washington Senators next reached the Fall Classic in 1933 – their last before they became the Minnesota Twins, and the city's last until the 2019 Nationals – Johnson had retired.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] This game remains to date the last road World Series game the Washington Senators/Minnesota Twins franchise has won.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] Walter Johnson pitched a complete game and allowed only five hits and struck out ten.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] The Senators got on the board in the second on Joe Harris's home run off Lee Meadows.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] In the fifth, they loaded the bases on three singles with no outs, but after Meadows struck out the next two batters, a two-run single by Sam Rice made it 3–0 Senators.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] Pie Traynor's leadoff home run in the bottom half gave the Pirates their only run in the game.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] The Senators added another run in the ninth off Johnny Morrison when Goose Goslin hit a leadoff single, moved to second on a sacrifice bunt and scored on Ossie Bluege's single.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] In Game 2, Joe Judge's second inning home run off Vic Aldridge gave the Senators a 1–0 lead, but the Pirates tied the game in the fourth on Glenn Wright's home run in the fourth off Stan Coveleski.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] In the eighth, Kiki Cuyler's two-run home run in the eighth following a Roger Peckinpaugh error that let Eddie Moore reached first put the Pirates up 3–1.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] In the ninth, the Senators loaded the bases with no outs on two walks and a single, but scored only once on Bobby Veach's sacrifice fly as Aldridge retired the next two batters and the Pirates tied the series heading to Washington.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] In Game 3, the Pirates struck first in the second when Pie Traynor hit a leadoff triple off Alex Ferguson and scored on Glenn Wright's sacrifice fly, but the Senators tied the game in the third off Ray Kremer when Sam Rice hit a leadoff single and scored on Joe Judge's double.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] The Pirates regained the lead in the fourth when Kiki Cuyler hit a leadoff single and scored on Clyde Barnhart's double.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] They added to their lead in the sixth on Kremer's RBI single with two on, but Goose Goslin's home run in the bottom half cut their lead back to one.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] Next inning, the Senators loaded the bases on a walk and two singles with one out before Judge's sacrifice fly tied the game, then an RBI single by Joe Harris put them up 4–3.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] A key play occurred in the eighth inning when Earl Smith's line drive into right-center field was caught by Sam Rice who fell into the temporary stands (see overview above).
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] Firpo Marberry pitched two shutout innings to close the game.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] This was Johnson's only post-season shutout.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] A three-run home run by Goose Goslin followed by a solo home run by Joe Harris off Emil Yde, who pitched just 2+1⁄3 innings, in the third inning put the Senators up 3–1 in the series.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] Yde became the first pitcher in the history of the World Series to surrender back-to-back home runs.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] The Pirates loaded the bases in the first, but failed to score.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] In the bottom half, Sam Rice hit a leadoff single and scored on Goose Goslin's double.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] In the third, after two walks, Clyde Barnhart's RBI single tied the game, then Pie Traynor's sacrifice fly put the Pirates up 2–1.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] Joe Harris's home run in the fourth tied the game.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] After a walk and single, back-to-back RBI singles by Kiki Cuyler and Clyde Barnhart in the seventh put the Pirates up 4–2 and knock Stan Coveleski out of the game.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] The Senators cut the lead to 4–3 in the bottom half when Nemo Leibold hit a leadoff double and scored on Sam Rice's single, but the Pirates got the run back in the eighth when Glenn Wright hit a leadoff double off Tom Zachary and scored on Stuffy McInnis's single.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] They added another run in the ninth on Wright's RBI single off Firpo Marberry with the run charged to Zachary.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] Vic Aldridge retired the Senators in order in the bottom half as the Pirates' 6–3 win forced a Game 6 in Pittsburgh.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] The Senators struck first on Goose Goslin's home run in the first, then added another run in the second on Roger Peckinpaugh's RBI double, but Pirates' Ray Kremer would shut them out afterward.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] In the third, with runners on second and third, Clyde Barnhart's groundout and Pie Traynor's single scored a run each to tie the game.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] Eddie Moore's fifth inning home run put the Pirates up 3–2.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] The Senators loaded the bases in the first on a single and two walks with one out.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] A walk to Joe Judge and RBI single by Ossie Bluege put them up 2–0 and knocked starter Vic Aldridge out of the game.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] Johnny Morrison came in relief, but a catcher interference call and error allowed two more runs to score.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] In the third, a leadoff single by Morrison, then RBI hits by Eddie Moore, Max Carey and Clyde Barnhart cut the Senators' lead to 4–3.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] In the fourth, Joe Harris's two-run double extended Washington's lead to 6–3.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] Back-to-back doubles by Carey and Kiki Cuyler in the fifth cut the lead to 6–4, then in the seventh, Moore reached first on an error before Carey's RBI double and Traynor's RBI triple tied the game.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] Roger Peckinpaugh's home run in the eighth off Ray Kremer put the Senators back atop 7–6, but in the bottom half, back-to-back two-out doubles by Earl Smith and Carson Bigbee tied the game.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] A walk and fielder's choice loaded the bases before Cuyler's two-run double put the Pirates atop 9–7.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] Red Oldham retired the Senators in order in the ninth to end the series.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] The Pirates hit Walter Johnson hard for 15 hits in a 9–7 comeback win in rainy, wet and muddy conditions.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] The Pirates were the first team to come back from a 3–1 deficit in a seven-game series.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] The Pirates returned to the World Series two years later in hopes of adding another championship, but were swept by the New York Yankees.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] They would not win the title again until 1960, in which they defeated the Yankees in seven games in a rematch.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1925-world-series] The Senators would make one more World Series in 1933, which they lost to the New York Giants in five games, which would be their last during their time in the nation’s capital, as the team would move to Minneapolis in 1961 to become the Minnesota Twins.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1932-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1932 throughout the world.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1932-in-baseball] All Negro leagues standings below are per MLB and Seamheads.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1932-in-baseball] 1932 was the only time the Negro Southern League was considered a major league.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1932-in-baseball] Chicago won the first half while Nashville won the second half.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1932-in-baseball] They matched up against each other in a best-of-seven postseason series, which Chicago won four to three.
[src:general-manager-baseball/1932-in-baseball] A loose confederation of teams existed that were not part of either established leagues.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] In Major League Baseball, the **general manager** (**GM**) of a team typically controls player transactions and bears the primary responsibility on behalf of the ballclub during contract discussions with players.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] The general manager is normally the person who hires and fires the coaching staff, including the field manager who acts as the head coach.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] In baseball, the term *manager* used without qualification almost always refers to the field manager, not the general manager.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] Before the 1960s, and in some rare cases since then, a person with the general manager title in sports has also borne responsibility for the non-player operations of the ballclub, such as ballpark administration and broadcasting.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] Ed Barrow, George Weiss and Gabe Paul were three baseball GMs noted for their administrative skills in both player and non-player duties.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] In the first decades of baseball's post-1901 modern era, responsibilities for player acquisition fell upon the club owner and/or president and the field manager.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] In some cases, particularly in the early years of the American League, the owner was a former player or manager himself: Charles Comiskey of the Chicago White Sox, Connie Mack of the Philadelphia Athletics, and Clark Griffith of the Washington Senators are three prominent examples.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] Other owners tended to be magnates from the business world, although some, like Brooklyn Dodgers' president Charles Ebbets, worked their way from front-office jobs into ownership positions.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] Most deferred player personnel evaluations to their on-field managers.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] Leavitt in their book *In Pursuit of Pennants*, was German immigrant Barney Dreyfuss, owner of the Pittsburgh Pirates from 1900 to 1932.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] Dreyfuss had no playing background, but was one of the most astute judges of talent of his time.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] Under Dreyfuss, Pittsburgh won six National League pennants and two World Series titles (1909 and 1925).
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] The New York Giants' John McGraw, who also held a minority ownership stake in the team, is an example of a powerful manager who, during his three decades at the Giants' helm, exerted control over off-field aspects of the team's operation.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] McGraw managed the Giants from 1902 to 1932, piloting them to ten National League pennants and three World Series titles (1905, 1921, and 1922) along the way.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] According to Baseball Almanac, the first man to hold the title of general manager was Billy Evans when he was appointed by the Cleveland Indians in 1927.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] However, the duties of the modern general manager already had been assumed by two executives — Barrow of the New York Yankees and Branch Rickey of the St.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] Louis Cardinals — whose formal title at the time was *business manager.* Both were former field managers of big-league teams, although Barrow had no professional playing background.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] They assumed those positions (Barrow in 1920 and Rickey five years later) when clubs could legally control only 15 minor league players on option, and most young players were purchased or drafted from independently owned minor league teams.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] The general manager, in lieu of the "owner-operator", provided that oversight.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] But both the owner-operator and the field-manager-as-GM models survived into the 1980s.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] Owners Charlie Finley of the Oakland Athletics and Calvin Griffith of the Minnesota Twins functioned as their own chiefs of baseball operations.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] The early decades of the 21st century have seen Major League Baseball teams create a new layer of authority between ownership and the general manager, typically called the **president of baseball operations** (**POBO**).
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] These executives may work in concert with others in the organization styled as presidents but having non-baseball-centric responsibilities, such as President/CEO or President/COO.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] The trend began in 2007, when, in June, Andy MacPhail was hired into a POBO role by the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] Then, in September, general manager Larry Beinfest was promoted to president of baseball operations by the Florida Marlins.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] In Beinfest's case, he was assisted by a newly appointed GM, Michael Hill.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] Writing for *Sports Business Daily* in March 2015, legal academic and sports lawyer Glenn M.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] In June 2015, another article by Wong revisited the topic and compared the evolving job descriptions and career trajectories of GMs and POBOs.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] The *Baseball America Annual Directory* of 2019 listed 12 POBOs among the 30 MLB teams, as well as one "chief baseball officer" and four "executive vice presidents of baseball operations", operating above the GM level or also holding the GM title.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] In April 2024, a ranking by *The Athletic* of the top 10 front offices in MLB included seven teams with a president of baseball operations, and three without.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] In some instances, a team may operate with a POBO or chief baseball officer and leave the GM role vacant.
[src:general-manager-baseball/general-manager-baseball] Two examples involve the Boston Red Sox: from 2017 through 2019, Dave Dombrowski served as POBO and the team had no GM; and in 2024, Craig Breslow served as chief baseball officer and the team again had no GM.
